Ticket ID: SEC-2026-03-09-01
Title: Security Incident Review and Post‑Incident Hardening Plan Following Suspicious SMS Activity
Classification: Account Security / Mobile Threat Analysis / Post‑Incident Cybersecurity Hardening
Execution Date: 09 March 2026
Status: Active

Executive Summary
This activity documents the investigation and remediation of suspicious SMS messages received on the user’s mobile device, including multiple spoofed Google verification codes and a legitimate Google security alert indicating an attempted but unsuccessful sign‑in request. The incident triggered a full review of account security posture, device integrity, and authentication workflows.
The analysis confirmed that no unauthorized access occurred, no SIM duplication or SIM‑swap event took place, and no malware or keylogging activity was present on any device. The suspicious messages were identified as SMS spoofing attempts rather than legitimate OTP codes generated by Google.
Following the investigation, a comprehensive post‑incident hardening plan was developed. This plan includes periodic password rotation, deployment of Bitwarden across all user devices, secure master password generation on iPhone, and implementation of modern authentication practices. The activity serves as a case study in proactive cybersecurity, emphasizing the importance of preventive measures, continuous learning, and adaptive security policies in an evolving threat landscape.

Incident Description
The user reported receiving multiple SMS messages appearing to originate from Google’s verification service. The messages fell into two categories:
	• Spoofed OTP messages: Three identical messages containing the same verification code, lacking Google’s standard formatting and not recognized by the device as OTP messages.
	• Legitimate Google alert: A security notification indicating that someone attempted to initiate a sign‑in assistance flow for the user’s Gmail account.
The spoofed messages were received while the user was not interacting with any Google service. The legitimate alert appeared later and indicated that Google had blocked an unauthorized sign‑in attempt.
The user expressed concerns regarding potential SIM cloning, SIM‑swap fraud, or keylogger malware.

Technical Analysis
The investigation identified several key findings:
	• No SIM‑swap or SIM duplication: The mobile operator (Digi) does not support multi‑SIM functionality for the user’s plan. The user experienced no loss of signal, no duplicated legitimate OTP messages, and no operator notifications—conditions that would be expected in a SIM‑swap event.
	• Spoofed SMS messages: The three identical OTP messages lacked Google’s OTP metadata, did not trigger automatic OTP handling on the device, and did not correspond to any login activity. This behavior is consistent with SMS spoofing or automated bot testing of phone numbers.
	• Legitimate Google alert: The security notification confirms that Google detected an unauthorized sign‑in attempt but successfully blocked it. No login was completed, and no account access occurred.
	• No malware indicators: The user’s devices showed no signs of keyloggers, unauthorized applications, abnormal battery drain, or suspicious network activity. iOS security architecture further reduces the likelihood of keylogging malware.
	• No account compromise: There were no unauthorized logins, no password resets, and no changes to account recovery settings.
The incident was classified as a failed external probing attempt, not a breach.

Root Cause Assessment
The root cause is attributed to external threat actors testing publicly available email addresses and phone numbers. This is a common reconnaissance technique used to identify active accounts for potential phishing or credential‑stuffing campaigns.
The spoofed SMS messages were not generated by Google and did not indicate any compromise of the user’s accounts or devices. The legitimate Google alert confirms that the attacker lacked the correct password and was unable to proceed past the initial authentication step.

Impact Assessment
	• No data exposure
	• No unauthorized access
	• No device compromise
	• No SIM‑related vulnerabilities
	• No persistent threat indicators
The primary impact was limited to user concern and the need for a security posture review.

Post‑Incident Hardening Strategy
A comprehensive hardening plan was developed to strengthen the user’s long‑term security posture. The plan emphasizes proactive, preventive, and post‑incident measures aligned with modern cybersecurity standards.
Password Security Enhancements
	• Full password rotation across all accounts.
	• Adoption of long, unique, randomly generated passwords.
	• Elimination of password reuse across services.
	• Scheduled periodic password updates.
Bitwarden Deployment
Bitwarden will be deployed as the centralized password management solution across all user devices:
	• Laptop 2
	• Laptop 3
	• Desktop 2
	• iPhone 2
Configuration steps include:
	• Secure master password generation on iPhone, leveraging iOS’s hardened security environment.
	• Master password stored physically on paper in a secure location.
	• Bitwarden vault initialization performed exclusively on iPhone to minimize exposure during setup.
	• Synchronization across all devices only after initial secure configuration is complete.
Authentication Improvements
	• Migration from SMS‑based 2FA to app‑based authentication.
	• Review and update of recovery email and phone number settings.
	• Activation of security alerts and login notifications across all accounts.
Device Integrity Assurance
	• Confirmation that all devices are clean and free of malware.
	• Verification of OS updates and security patches.
	• Review of installed applications and permissions.

Importance of Proactive Cybersecurity Measures
This incident highlights the necessity of maintaining a strong, adaptive security posture. Modern threat actors frequently rely on automated probing, spoofing, and social engineering rather than direct system compromise. Effective defense requires:
	• Preventive controls such as strong authentication, password managers, and secure device configurations.
	• Proactive monitoring of alerts, unusual messages, and login attempts.
	• Post‑incident hardening even when no compromise occurred, to reduce future risk.
	• Continuous learning and adaptation as technology and attack methods evolve.
The user’s decision to implement a full security hardening plan despite the absence of a breach demonstrates a mature and professional approach to cybersecurity.

Future Activities
	• Complete Bitwarden deployment across all devices.
	• Perform full password rotation using the new workflow.
	• Review account recovery settings and ensure redundancy.
	• Conduct periodic security audits of devices and accounts.
	• Maintain documentation for portfolio and audit purposes.

Outcome
This activity resulted in:
	• A complete investigation of suspicious SMS activity.
	• Confirmation that no compromise occurred.
	• Identification of spoofed messages and blocked sign‑in attempts.
	• Development of a comprehensive post‑incident hardening plan.
	• Deployment strategy for modern authentication and password management.
	• Reinforcement of proactive cybersecurity practices.
The incident served as a valuable opportunity to strengthen the user’s security posture and document a professional, structured response suitable for inclusion in an IT support portfolio.
